  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: How does CONCAT function work in Hive?
  answer: Hive provides CONCAT function to concatenate the input strings. We can specify multiple strings in a comma-separated list. here is another function CONCAT_WS in Hive that can be used to specify the custom delimiter.
- id: scraped-q-537
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: How will you change settings of a Hive session?
  answer: |
    We can use SET command to change the settings within a Hive Session. We can even change the settings of MapReduce job with SET command. If we just call SET command with a property name, we will get the current value of the property.
    With SET -v we get the list of all the properties including Hadoop default in Hive system.
- id: scraped-q-538
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: How will you rename a table in Hive without using ALTER command?
  answer: |
    We can use IMPORT/EXPORT statements to rename a table in Hive. We first export the original table to a location by EXPORT statement.
    hive>	EXPORT	TABLE tableName	TO ’TEMP_LOCATION’
    Then we create new table with IMPORT statement.
    hive>	IMPORT	TABLE newTableName	FROM ’TEMP_LOCATION’
- id: scraped-q-539
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: EASY
  question: What is the difference between SORT BY and ORDER BY in Hive?
  answer: |
    In Hive we use, SORT BY to sort data in each Reducer. We can use multiple Reducers in SORT BY clause.
    We can use ORDER BY to sort all the data that passes through one Reducer. So ORDER BY option can be use only with one Reducer.
    ORDER BY guarantees total order in the output. SORT BY guarantees ordering only within the data of one reducer.
- id: scraped-q-540
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: What is the use of strict mode in Hive?
  answer: We use strict mode in Hive to avoid performing full scan of a table in a query. It is very useful when we have a very large table. We	can	use	set hive.mapred.mode=strict command to put Hive into strict mode. In this mode, any query that needs full table scan will throw error to user. Strict mode is a useful option in Hive to improve performance and avoid any unexpected delays due to full table scan.
- id: scraped-q-541
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: What is the use of IF EXISTS clause in Hive statements?
  answer: We use IF EXISTS clause in DROP TABLE statement. When we drop a table, there can be a case that table does not exist. In such a case DROP statement will give error. In case we are not sure if the table exists or not in Hive, we use DROP TABLE IF EXISTS tableName statement to drop a table. This statement will not give error in case table does not exist.
- id: scraped-q-542
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: What is the use of PURGE in DROP statement of Hive?
  answer: We use PURGE option when we are absolutely sure to delete the data of a table. With DROP TABLE tableName PURGE statement, table data will not go to trash folder. So it cannot be retrieved in case of an accidental DROP statement.
- id: scraped-q-543
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: What are the main limitations of Apache Hive?
  answer: |
    Apache Hive is a popular tool in Hadoop eco-system. Some of the limitations of Hive are as follows:
    OLTP: Hive cannot be used for OLTP applications, since it does not support record level update, insert statements.
    Data Warehouse: Hive is more suitable for data warehouse	applications	on Big Data.
    Latency: Hive queries have higher latency than SQL due to time overhead during start-up.
    Batch Oriented: Hive is mostly used in Batch- oriented use cases.
    OLAP: For Online Analytic Processing (OLAP) we can use Hive. We can use HBase also for OLAP processing.
- id: scraped-q-544
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: EASY
  question: What is the difference between HBase and Hive?
  answer: HBase is a NoSQL database. It supports update, insert and delete statements at record level. HBase does not support a query language like SQL. But we can use Hive with HBase for querying purpose. Hive runs on MapReduce. HBase runs on HDFS. Apache Hive is a data warehousing and data analytics framework that is used for data warehouse applications. HBase is a NoSQL database on top of HDFS.
- id: scraped-q-545
  source: General Data Engineering
  category: Databases & SQL
  niche: 
  difficulty: MEDIUM
  question: What is ObjectInspector in Hive?
  answer: ObjectInspector is used in Hive to look into the internal structure of a complex object. It is an interface that is implemented by classes like StandardListObjectInspector, StandardMapObjectInspector, StandardSetObjectInspector etc. Main use of ObjectInspector is in SerDe package for Serialization and Deserialization. We have to make sure that hashCode() and equals() methods of Object class work for ObjectInspector as well.
